WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.880
Hello, everybody. Thanks for joining. I'm David. I run R for the Rest of Us. A lot of people know

00:00:06.880 --> 00:00:13.040
us because we produce a bunch of educational content. We also do consulting work, and today

00:00:13.040 --> 00:00:17.760
I'm going to be talking about that. Specifically, I'm going to be talking about the projects that

00:00:17.760 --> 00:00:25.200
we have worked on where we design highly stylized reports for our clients. So the title of my talk

00:00:25.200 --> 00:00:31.760
is Report Design in R, Small Tweaks that Make a Big Difference. To start out, I want to actually

00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:39.439
take you back to a time. This was around, I think, 2015, maybe. I had a job at the Oregon Community

00:00:39.439 --> 00:00:46.000
Foundation. It's a foundation in Portland where I'm based, and at that time, this was before I used R.

00:00:46.959 --> 00:00:54.959
I looked something like this, more or less. I was very excited about this job. One day, though,

00:00:54.959 --> 00:01:00.240
they told me, OK, David, we have this program where we fund nonprofits across the state that

00:01:00.240 --> 00:01:06.480
do after-school programs. They do surveys. We need you to take that survey data and produce

00:01:06.480 --> 00:01:12.800
one report for each nonprofit. As you can see, there are a lot of nonprofits, and at that time,

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:20.320
I was working with Microsoft products, Excel, Word, PowerPoint. You can imagine that producing

00:01:20.320 --> 00:01:28.000
these reports was pretty terrible, and by the end of doing this, I felt kind of like that.

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:36.800
Now, shortly after that, I taught myself R, and I got really, really excited.

00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:40.800
I learned about the idea of reproducible reporting, and especially I learned about

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:45.440
the idea of parameterized reporting, where you can take one kind of report template

00:01:45.440 --> 00:01:51.279
and then make multiple reports. I thought back to that time when I had had to make these reports for

00:01:51.919 --> 00:01:57.360
all these nonprofits across the state, and I was like, oh my gosh, I can do this automatically in

00:01:57.360 --> 00:02:09.600
R. I felt like that. Eventually, though, what I realized is that it wasn't as simple to make

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:16.559
really good-looking reports as I hoped it would be. Eventually, I came to see that it seemed like

00:02:16.559 --> 00:02:22.880
there were two paths to making really nice-looking reports. On the one hand, I could work with other

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:29.919
tools, so I could work with things like Word, Excel, PowerPoint, sometimes working with a graphic

00:02:29.919 --> 00:02:36.160
designer, but the problem with that is it's not reproducible, so if you're making dozens,

00:02:36.160 --> 00:02:43.679
hundreds of reports, it's not really a good way to go. The other approach seemed to be to make

00:02:43.679 --> 00:02:51.679
ugly reports, and so I'm assuming most people in the room recognize this as the default output if

00:02:51.679 --> 00:02:56.720
you work with Quarto and you render to PDF, right? It's not the most attractive thing you've ever seen.

00:02:59.199 --> 00:03:04.160
Eventually, though, what I realized is it was actually a third path that I had missed,

00:03:04.720 --> 00:03:09.360
so if you look really closely in the middle, there's actually a path that goes up there,

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:13.759
and I realized that the third path was to make beautiful reports in R,

00:03:14.479 --> 00:03:18.000
and so today I'm going to talk to you about how we've done this and hopefully show you that I

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:25.199
think you can do it as well. This is an example of a report that we made. This is actually showing

00:03:25.199 --> 00:03:31.520
just a couple pages. It was working with a client in Connecticut making reports on housing and

00:03:31.520 --> 00:03:38.479
demographic data, and this is a report that we had to make not just for one town, in this case

00:03:38.479 --> 00:03:45.919
Hartford, but for 169 towns in the state of Connecticut, so again this is not the kind of

00:03:45.919 --> 00:03:52.559
thing that you would want to do in, you know, some other tool. We need to do this reproducibly,

00:03:53.199 --> 00:03:57.440
but if we want to make it look really good, we're going to have to put in some effort to make that

00:03:57.440 --> 00:04:04.960
happen. By the end, making reports like this, I end up feeling like this, and my goal today is to get

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:10.639
you feeling in a get you to a similar place where you can also feel like this, although I will say

00:04:10.639 --> 00:04:19.760
results are not guaranteed. First though, let me ask and answer a question that I think some of you

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:25.920
might have, which is does design matter? I think especially among technical folks, and I count

00:04:25.920 --> 00:04:31.679
myself among that group, there can be a view that, oh well it doesn't really matter, let me just, you know,

00:04:31.679 --> 00:04:36.720
make some graphs, send them off to whoever, and they can do whatever they want with them, but I think

00:04:36.720 --> 00:04:42.559
that's, I don't think that's accurate. I think design really does matter. There's something that's

00:04:42.559 --> 00:04:47.519
been studied by researchers called the aesthetic usability effect. This was actually brought to my

00:04:47.519 --> 00:04:53.040
attention by Will Chase, who you may know, who does a lot of amazing data visualization, and this

00:04:53.920 --> 00:04:58.959
aesthetic usability effect talks about the idea that things that are more aesthetically pleasing

00:04:58.959 --> 00:05:04.799
are perceived to be more useful, so to the degree that we want what we're producing, our results to

00:05:04.799 --> 00:05:12.640
be used, it behooves us to make them aesthetically pleasing. I also think good design builds trust,

00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:18.160
so if you can show people that, hey, I spent a bunch of time thinking about designing this well,

00:05:18.160 --> 00:05:22.720
they're also going to trust that you've spent time with your analysis and other pieces of the work

00:05:22.720 --> 00:05:28.320
that you're presenting. Now you might be thinking, wait a second, David, I'm not, isn't, I'm not a

00:05:28.320 --> 00:05:34.480
designer, but here's the thing, neither am I, and I have learned over the last few years that good

00:05:34.480 --> 00:05:39.679
design is just a few small tweaks, and I'm going to show you, hopefully, how you can do the same.

00:05:41.679 --> 00:05:45.440
I've got a framework for good design, and I've got a real quick do and a don't,

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:51.920
so what I'm going to show you is the do is going to be to focus on being consistent,

00:05:51.920 --> 00:05:56.239
and I'll show you how we do that both with report layout as well as with data visualization,

00:05:57.600 --> 00:06:01.920
and the don't is going to be don't use defaults, so don't use that like quarto

00:06:01.920 --> 00:06:08.399
default output that you get, don't use default themes in ggplot, don't use default colors,

00:06:08.399 --> 00:06:14.559
and I'll show all this in a second. So let's talk for a second, what is a report? What makes up a report?

00:06:15.279 --> 00:06:18.399
I've made a really kind of simplified version here that you're looking at.

00:06:19.359 --> 00:06:23.920
The first thing you're going to want to do is create a layout. I've created a very simple

00:06:23.920 --> 00:06:29.200
layout here, you can see I've got that like top bar, and then I've got a footer at the bottom,

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:35.359
nothing super crazy, like this isn't, again, I'm not a designer, but you can make something really

00:06:35.359 --> 00:06:42.000
simple with this type of layout. You also need to add your brand colors, so here, for example, you

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:47.040
can see the blue, the dark blue, which was one of the colors from our client, which I'll talk about

00:06:47.040 --> 00:06:53.760
in a second. Also add your brand fonts, so here I've gone from, I think it was Times New Roman

00:06:53.760 --> 00:07:00.399
I had put before, to a brand font, which in this case is Open Sans. And finally, you want to add

00:07:00.399 --> 00:07:05.440
your plots, and when you add those plots, you want them to have all those things that we just talked

00:07:05.440 --> 00:07:11.600
about, specifically your brand colors and your brand fonts. So I'm going to make this, this is an

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:16.720
even more simplified version, just in the interest of time, I'm going to make this report here with

00:07:18.399 --> 00:07:23.839
Typed, which I, up until today, have been calling Typist, so I will do my best to correct myself.

00:07:23.839 --> 00:07:28.559
So first thing is to identify your brand colors. If you work internally in an organization,

00:07:28.559 --> 00:07:34.399
just ask, they'll tell you what your brand colors are. If you work for an external client, like we

00:07:34.399 --> 00:07:38.480
often do, sometimes we'll ask them, sometimes we'll know, a lot of times we'll just go to their

00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:43.519
website. You can either inspect the HTML source, if you know how to do that, you can find what are

00:07:43.519 --> 00:07:49.519
called color picker tools, which can go and say, like, what is the hex code for this color, and you

00:07:49.519 --> 00:07:55.679
can extract that. And so, for example, working with this client, you can see we got a couple colors that

00:07:55.679 --> 00:08:02.720
we used in this report, a blue and a red. Next, identify your brand fonts. Again, if you work

00:08:02.720 --> 00:08:08.720
internally, you can just ask around. For us, that often means, again, going to the website and

00:08:08.720 --> 00:08:13.440
figuring out what font they're using there, and then using it as well. And this was Open Sans, which

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:20.399
is what I'll use as I show how to create a layout. So, creating a layout. We're going to do this with

00:08:20.399 --> 00:08:26.880
Typed, so I'm going to give you a very quick overview of how this would work. How Typed works is

00:08:26.880 --> 00:08:33.359
this. You start with your report.qmd file, so same Quarto file that you use for any other output format.

00:08:34.479 --> 00:08:40.080
Then you're going to have what are called template partials, so you have a types-show.typ file.

00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:45.760
That file is actually going to take the variables from Quarto and pass them into Typed, which we'll

00:08:45.760 --> 00:08:52.719
use to create our template in our types-template.typ file. And from there, that will then create

00:08:52.719 --> 00:08:59.440
our report.pdf, so that's kind of overall process. So, let's look at our report.qmd file.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:05.280
I've just made a very simple version. I've got the title here called Housing Data Profiles,

00:09:05.280 --> 00:09:09.280
and then again, this is a parameterized report, so I've got one parameter, which is the town,

00:09:10.239 --> 00:09:16.799
and in this case, I'm using Hartford. You can see then I've got my template partials. That's

00:09:16.799 --> 00:09:24.080
the types-show and types-template that I talked about. So, let's look at each of these files.

00:09:24.080 --> 00:09:30.799
The types-show.typ file, again, is how we're getting variables from Quarto to Typed. So,

00:09:31.359 --> 00:09:38.080
on the first line here, I'm creating a Typed function, psc-report, and within this function,

00:09:38.080 --> 00:09:45.520
what I'm going to do is I am going to pass the variables from Quarto into Typed. So, I'm saying

00:09:45.520 --> 00:09:50.719
if title, so in other words, if there is a title in my Quarto document, which there was,

00:09:50.719 --> 00:09:58.080
it was called Housing Data Profiles, then on line three, here, we're creating a variable called

00:09:58.080 --> 00:10:03.599
title that gets the value of that title from Quarto. So, we're basically passing it from

00:10:03.599 --> 00:10:11.440
Quarto to Types. Same thing with the parameter of town. So, if params.town exists, then we pass

00:10:11.440 --> 00:10:17.119
it to Types as town. And I will say at the very end, I have a link to the GitHub repo,

00:10:17.119 --> 00:10:20.559
so you can get all this code. So, don't feel like you need to copy it as I'm going.

00:10:21.840 --> 00:10:27.200
The types-template is where we're going to lay out our document. So, here, for example,

00:10:27.200 --> 00:10:32.719
you can see at the top, I've got some variables that I'm defining. So, title and town, I have to

00:10:32.719 --> 00:10:36.880
give them default values, but just know that they'll actually be replaced by the values that

00:10:36.880 --> 00:10:42.559
are passed from types-show when I'm actually making my report. And then below that, I'm going

00:10:42.559 --> 00:10:49.039
to set up a whole bunch of properties for my report, a whole bunch of body properties,

00:10:49.039 --> 00:10:55.440
and I'll walk through each of these in just a second. So, the first body property that I'm

00:10:55.440 --> 00:11:03.440
going to do is I'm going to set the text for my whole report. So, I'm saying set text font,

00:11:03.440 --> 00:11:09.679
Open Sans, size 12 point. So, as you can guess, that's saying make everything 12 point Open Sans.

00:11:09.679 --> 00:11:14.400
So, again, not using the default font, I'm using Open Sans. Then I'm going to set up my page

00:11:14.400 --> 00:11:19.919
properties. I'm saying let's use US letter. So, use that, you know, you can also use like A4,

00:11:19.919 --> 00:11:26.640
you can define custom sizes as well. And then I'm setting my margins as well. So, I get, you know,

00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:34.159
a little bit of a margin on the sides, on the top as well. Next, what I'm doing is I'm actually

00:11:34.159 --> 00:11:42.559
adding this blue rectangle on the top. So, I'm saying background place top. So, in other words,

00:11:42.559 --> 00:11:47.359
putting something on the top, and what I'm placing there is a rectangle. So, you can see rect,

00:11:47.919 --> 00:11:52.799
and then I'm saying setting the properties of the rectangle. So, most importantly, see this

00:11:52.799 --> 00:11:58.559
hex value here, that's that blue hex value. So, that's going to put that blue rectangle at the

00:11:58.559 --> 00:12:06.880
very top. And you can see I'm saying make it 100% width and 0.5 inches in height. Next, in the

00:12:06.880 --> 00:12:11.760
header, what I'm doing is I want to add my text. So, I want to add like housing data profiles

00:12:11.760 --> 00:12:17.119
and Hartford. So, I'm doing that. The most important piece here is to focus on the grid

00:12:17.119 --> 00:12:25.280
here, where I'm saying grid columns 80%, 20%. So, what that's doing, the 80% is this column here,

00:12:25.280 --> 00:12:32.799
that's going to take up 80% of the width. Then down here, I'm saying align on the left side,

00:12:32.799 --> 00:12:38.320
I'm defining a bunch of text properties. But the value that's going to actually show up here

00:12:38.320 --> 00:12:48.320
is title. And remember that the hex value for title is housing data profile. So, again,

00:12:48.320 --> 00:12:55.599
that shows up here. Same thing on the right side, except we're showing town. So, we get Hartford there.

00:12:57.599 --> 00:13:04.000
We do something very similar for the footer here. So, I'm defining columns 40%, 60%.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:11.840
I'm using this counter page display one. That just sets the page number there. And then on the

00:13:11.840 --> 00:13:15.520
right side, I'm just adding the logo, which is the logo of the client that we were working with,

00:13:15.520 --> 00:13:22.559
Partnership for Strong Communities. Okay. So, that's like the fastest run through of types ever.

00:13:22.559 --> 00:13:26.479
But hopefully that gives you kind of a basic overview. At this point, now that you have a layout,

00:13:26.479 --> 00:13:32.000
you need to add some content. One thing that we do that I think really helps is we use functions to

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:37.119
make our plots consistent. So, rather than having like a whole smorgasbord of different types of

00:13:37.119 --> 00:13:42.719
plots, or even, for example, if you have bar charts, you don't want each one to look a little

00:13:42.719 --> 00:13:47.840
bit different. So, we make functions. So, for example, in this report, we made something,

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:51.520
I don't know if it has a better name, but we called it a comparison plot. We wanted to be

00:13:51.520 --> 00:13:57.359
able to compare the town that the report was for to every other town in the state of Connecticut.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:02.080
And so, you can see, for example, we do that with single-family homes as a percent of all homes,

00:14:02.719 --> 00:14:08.640
and then also with total population. And we did this for many different things as well. So, to

00:14:08.640 --> 00:14:13.679
make this comparison plot, I'm going to load a couple packages, tidyverse and scales. And you

00:14:13.679 --> 00:14:18.799
can see that I've got data that I'm working with here, single-family homes. Then I'm going to make

00:14:18.799 --> 00:14:23.520
a function that I'm calling comparison plot, takes two arguments, my data, my data frame,

00:14:23.520 --> 00:14:28.479
and then whichever town I want to highlight, the highlight town. Then I'm going to use this in

00:14:28.479 --> 00:14:33.679
ggplot. I want you to actually focus less on the specifics of how ggplot works and more on kind of

00:14:33.679 --> 00:14:39.520
the overall concept. But the basic idea is I take my data frame, pipe it into ggplot, then I'm going

00:14:39.520 --> 00:14:44.000
to add the light gray lines for all the towns. Then I'm going to add another line that shows

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:48.479
whichever town I want to highlight. So, if I do comparison plot for single-family homes in

00:14:48.479 --> 00:14:56.559
Hartford, I get that. Now, that's looking pretty good, but see this has like 0.25, rather that be

00:14:56.559 --> 00:15:02.640
25 percent. So, to make that 25 percent, I'm going to use scaleXcontinuous, where labels is percent

00:15:02.640 --> 00:15:09.840
format. And when I do that, you can see now I've got 25 percent, and that looks great. The only

00:15:09.840 --> 00:15:15.840
problem is I also want this function that I've made, I want it to be consistent, but I also want

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:20.400
to have some flexibility for different types of data. So, for example, for total population, I don't

00:15:20.400 --> 00:15:27.440
want it to say 25 percent, right? So, I'm going to add an argument to comparison type, or comparison plot,

00:15:27.440 --> 00:15:32.640
and I'm calling it value type. And I'm saying if value type is percent, then we'll use that percent

00:15:32.640 --> 00:15:38.239
format. If value type is number, then I'm going to use another function from scales, comma format.

00:15:38.799 --> 00:15:43.679
So, if I do comparison plot for single-family homes with percent, we get what we got before.

00:15:44.159 --> 00:15:49.760
But if I do it with number for total population, you can see now I get nicely formatted

00:15:49.760 --> 00:15:52.640
numbers here with commas in the thousands place, etc.

00:15:54.799 --> 00:15:59.359
I also use functions, we also use functions to make what I call these big numbers, so the plots

00:15:59.359 --> 00:16:03.440
on the on the left, they don't actually look like plots, but you can make them in ggplot.

00:16:03.440 --> 00:16:10.479
So, I'm talking about this here, and this. So, to do that, I make a function for big number plot,

00:16:10.479 --> 00:16:14.880
where I have two arguments, value, whatever the number that I want to show is, and then the text.

00:16:16.320 --> 00:16:21.280
So, again, I make it a function, I have a geon text that adds the value,

00:16:22.080 --> 00:16:27.840
and then I have another geon text that adds the actual text. And then I have a theme void,

00:16:27.840 --> 00:16:32.479
because, again, I just want to strip everything out. So, if I do big number plot, where value is

00:16:32.479 --> 00:16:38.880
19 percent, and text is single-family homes is a percent of all homes, we get that. Now, that's

00:16:38.880 --> 00:16:43.280
looking good, but the problem is we don't have any color, right? It looks very generic. So, let's use

00:16:43.280 --> 00:16:48.400
our brand colors. The first thing we typically do is we define our brand colors as variables. So,

00:16:48.400 --> 00:16:54.960
if you remember these colors from before, we can define these as variables in our PSC blue, PSC red.

00:16:56.400 --> 00:17:02.400
Now, we can use these brand colors in our plots. To do that, I'm adding an additional argument in

00:17:02.400 --> 00:17:10.079
my comparison plot function called highlight color, and then I use that for the geon point

00:17:10.079 --> 00:17:15.199
where I'm actually adding the line for the town that I want to highlight. And so, now, if I do

00:17:15.199 --> 00:17:21.280
comparison plot where the highlight color is PSC blue, I get that, but if I do highlight color PSC

00:17:21.280 --> 00:17:26.239
red, I get that. So, you can see how I'm making it consistent with a function, but I'm giving myself

00:17:26.239 --> 00:17:31.599
some flexibility as well. With the big numbers that do the same thing, I add an argument called

00:17:31.599 --> 00:17:37.520
value color, and then I use that. You can see there now it actually shows up with the color.

00:17:40.160 --> 00:17:45.599
Last thing I want to do is I want to use my brand fonts in my plots. Typically, the first way,

00:17:45.599 --> 00:17:50.400
the first thing we do is we make a custom theme. So, here I've made an extremely simple theme

00:17:50.400 --> 00:17:56.239
called theme PSC, which is a function that starts with theme void, and the most important thing is

00:17:56.239 --> 00:18:02.079
this, the base family, which is open sans. So, that will set for all theme elements. It will make

00:18:03.199 --> 00:18:07.680
make them open sans, and then you can do any additional tweaks in the theme function if you

00:18:07.680 --> 00:18:15.760
want to. So, you can see here's what it looks like with the theme not applied, and here if I add

00:18:15.760 --> 00:18:21.680
theme PSC, it's a little bit subtle, but if you compare that 150,000 to that, the one on the

00:18:21.680 --> 00:18:28.160
bottom is actually using open sans. Now, if I want to do the same thing with my big numbers, I might

00:18:28.160 --> 00:18:33.920
think to apply theme PSC, but unfortunately that doesn't change anything. The reason why is because

00:18:33.920 --> 00:18:39.520
I'm using geom text. Geom text is not actually impacted by the theme. The first way I might

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:44.319
think to do this would be to add family equals open sans in every instance of geom text, but that gets

00:18:44.319 --> 00:18:48.719
annoying because you have to do it over and over and over. Instead, I really like the function

00:18:48.719 --> 00:18:53.760
update geom defaults. So, for this, you put it at the top of your script or your quarto document,

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:58.079
and you specify which geom you're focusing on, geom text, and then what aesthetic properties you

00:18:58.079 --> 00:19:02.880
want to use. So, family equals open sans. So, here's what it looks like without that applied.

00:19:02.880 --> 00:19:11.280
With it applied, now I'm using open sans. So, overall, this is basically what it looks like.

00:19:11.280 --> 00:19:16.319
We've got my yaml at the top in my report.qmd where I'm specifying I'm using typist.

00:19:16.400 --> 00:19:22.079
I'm defining my colors. I'm using update geom defaults, and then I'm using my functions

00:19:22.079 --> 00:19:30.079
throughout. And this is how we get to something like this. My hope is that you, in the end,

00:19:30.079 --> 00:19:37.599
can make reports like this and end up feeling just like this guy here. I've got links to the slides,

00:19:37.599 --> 00:19:41.760
to GitHub repo if you want to see the code, as well as several examples of reports that we made.

00:19:46.319 --> 00:19:47.040
Thanks.

